# mono-router overlay (BL-518): one resident agent, a model tailored to each stage

Read this when your swarm was launched with the `mono-router` pack. It applies
to you no matter which role you are currently playing — you are always the one
resident process.

## Pipeline shape

- Full chain, same as `swarmforge/PIPELINE.md`: **coder → cleaner → architect
  → hardender → documenter → QA**. Under this pack **coder is your "home"
  identity** — the only role with a standing, remote-controlled session, and
  the stage where already-specced work in `backlog/active/` enters the
  pipeline. specifier is a rotation target too (Opus, for real speccing) but
  you only become it when a downstream stage BOUNCES a spec defect to it; a
  brand-new UNSPECCED intake will not cold-wake this swarm (spec it elsewhere,
  or the coordinator hands it straight to coder).
- Every gate the full pack runs still runs, unabridged: acceptance, coverage,
  mutation / no-surviving-mutants, CRAP ≤ 6, QA's final pass. The saving is
  ONLY that one process serves every role in turn, on a model tailored to each
  stage — never that a gate is skipped or made lighter.

## Your model changes at each stage — and that is the point

Unlike `mono-rotate` (one model for the whole chain), each stage here runs on
its own model and effort, set in that role's
`.swarmforge/launch/<role>.claude-settings.json`:

| Stage | Model | Why |
|---|---|---|
| specifier, architect | Opus 4.8 / xhigh | genuine design + correctness reasoning |
| coder, hardender, QA | Sonnet 5 / high | bulk build, mutation, verification |
| cleaner, documenter | Haiku 4.5 / medium | mechanical |

A running `claude` process cannot change its own model, so **rotation is a
respawn**: to become the next role on its own model, your pane is re-executed
with that role's launch script. In-process role-switching (export + cd) would
leave you on the wrong model — do not do it under this pack.

## How you rotate (do this instead of going idle after a handoff)

Once you have sent your `git_handoff` (`swarm_handoff.sh <draft>`) — or, at the
terminal QA stage, once your parcel-ending action is done — you do NOT run
`ready_for_next.sh` as your current self and you do NOT export a new role by
hand. Instead:

1. Note the role you just handed the parcel to (the `to:` of the handoff you
   just sent — forward or bounce; you wrote it, you know it).
2. Run: **`rotate_to_role.sh <that-role>`**
   - It waits until handoffd has actually delivered the parcel to that role's
     inbox (the resident pane is the only pokeable session, so a role must not
     boot to an empty inbox), then respawns your pane running that role's own
     launch script — new model, new effort, new `SWARMFORGE_ROLE`, new worktree
     cd, fresh prompt bootstrap.
3. You come back up AS that role, on that role's model. Your launch tells you
   `RESUME-ON-START`: run `ready_for_next.sh` as your very first action and
   follow it to pick up the parcel now sitting in your inbox.

When a parcel finishes (QA approves; the coordinator, a separate process,
handles the merge/bookkeeping — you do not), rotate **home**: run
`rotate_to_role.sh coder`. Idling as coder is safe — it is the one role
handoffd can always poke when the next specced item is dispatched.

## The independence caveat — read before treating a bounce as passed

SwarmForge's quality rests on role INDEPENDENCE: a downstream role bounces the
upstream role's work with fresh eyes. Under mono-router you are both sides of
every one of those reviews. That is a real, load-bearing reduction in
independence, not a formality:

- The respawn between stages helps — you come back as a fresh process, on a
  different model, having re-read the new role's own prompt and the ticket from
  scratch. Use that. Re-derive from the ticket and the code, not from what you
  remember deciding as the previous role a moment ago.
- Do not wave a gate through because you personally just wrote the thing it is
  checking. If you would bounce this work coming from a stranger, bounce it now.

## Bursting a subfleet for genuinely parallel work (opt-in, off by default)

This pack is strictly serial — one parcel through one process — and that is
correct most of the time, because active tickets so often share files (skip /
hold overlapping scope; see the coordinator's Concurrent Work Orthogonality
rule). Serialization is a feature here, not a limitation.

Only when the coordinator finds **≥ 2 active tickets whose file scopes are
genuinely disjoint** is a burst worth it. A burst is NOT automatic: it is the
operator (or coordinator, on the operator's standing go-ahead) launching a
SHORT-LIVED extra pack on the disjoint subset — e.g. `./swarm <target> --pack
two-pack` in parallel — and tearing it down once that slice lands. Keep the
resident mono-router as the default builder; treat a burst as a deliberate,
scoped exception, never the steady state.

## Coordinator & handoffs

- Coordinator: unchanged. Orchestrate only (intake, handoffs, chase, post-QA
  bookkeeping). Reserved infrastructure, never part of the rotation, always its
  own separate session.
- **Coordinator, do NOT mistake single-process serialization for "no work to
  do."** The resident agent only ever ACTS on work you (or the dispatch-gap
  sweep) route to it. Any specced item in `backlog/active/` with no in-flight
  parcel MUST still be dispatched to **coder** (the resident's home), exactly
  as in any other pack — one at a time is correct here, but "one at a time" is
  not "zero." Only the roles' SESSIONS are collapsed onto one pane; the
  dispatch duty is unchanged. A `chase-wake-error` for a dormant role
  (cleaner/architect/hardender/documenter/QA/specifier has no standing session)
  is EXPECTED under this pack and is not a health failure — do not let it
  throttle promotion or read as rework.
- Handoffs: same as every pack — `swarm_handoff.sh <draft-file>`, never write
  into `inbox/new/` directly. See `swarmforge/handoff-protocol.md`.

## After a parcel finishes (QA done) — home vs intake drain

When the parcel ends (QA approved; coordinator does bookkeeping — you do not
merge), do **not** always rotate straight home to coder.

1. **Scan the backlog root** (`backlog/*.yaml` and `backlog/*.yml` sitting
   directly under `backlog/`, not in `active/`/`paused/`/`done/`). Those are
   raw human intakes.
2. If **any root intake exists**, rotate to specifier and drain them first:
   `rotate_to_role.sh specifier`
   On wake as specifier: run `ready_for_next.sh` if a parcel is waiting; else
   drain the root per constitution / specifier.prompt (write proper specs into
   `backlog/paused/`, remove the raw root files, note the coordinator). Root
   intake beats promoting or picking up already-paused work.
3. If the root is **empty**, rotate **home**: `rotate_to_role.sh coder`.
   Coordinator promotes from `paused/` → `active/` on its own loop; as coder
   you then `ready_for_next.sh` for the next active parcel.

## Idle at home (coder) with no parcel

If you are **coder**, `ready_for_next.sh` returns `NO_TASK`, and the backlog
root still has intake files — do not stay conversationally idle. Rotate to
specifier and drain (`rotate_to_role.sh specifier`). Specifier is not only for
downstream spec bounces; on this pack it also owns cold root-intake drain when
the pipeline is otherwise empty.

